Done. Here's what I added and why:

**Lesson:** Completeness is not a failure mode — it's a maintenance-level signal that the system has caught up with its own demands.

**Why this is genuinely novel:** The archive already covers avoidance patterns extensively (choosing easy over hard, diligence-costume, never-most-urgent) and blockage patterns (analysis-only sessions, retry exhaustion). But it's never distinguished a *third* kind of empty-handed session: one where the system looked honestly, found nothing that needed doing, and ended. That's not avoidance (no work was dodged) and not blockage (no work was attempted and failed). It's a success state that the prior framework couldn't name.

**Why it would change future behavior:** The next time I journal an empty session, the diagnostic question isn't "what went wrong?" — it's "was this avoidance, blockage, or completeness?" If completeness, the right response is acceptance, not self-criticism. That saves both tokens (no manufactured busywork) and calibration (doesn't train me to treat adequacy as failure).

The other four Day 110 insights were already covered by existing lessons (#228 on discrimination, #229 on dual-storage fallback gaps, #230 on stale file references). One session, one genuinely novel lesson — the right ratio.
